                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/909.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Mr. <persName type="to">Parker</persName>, representing American interests
                        in Mexico</hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-11-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 27, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department encloses a copy of a despatch [of
                    November 5] from the Vice Consul at Guadalajara, Mexico, setting forth the
                    arbitrary manner in which mining interests are being treated by the present de
                    facto government in Mexico.</p>
                <p>You are instructed to bring the statements contained therein to the attention of
                    the appropriate authorities, in connection with previous representations, and
                    earnestly to continue your efforts for a material modification of the decree
                    imposing increased taxes upon mining properties.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Acting Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilbur J. Carr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
